  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations regarding anti-money laundering (AML) efforts. These typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Monitoring transactions\n- Reporting suspicious activities\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Implementing Know Your Customer (KYC) procedures\n- Conducting risk assessments\n\n4. Training\n- Educating employees about money laundering risks\n- Training staff to identify suspicious transactions\n\n5. Record Keeping\n- Maintaining detailed transaction records\n- Preserving documentation for specified periods\n\n6. Internal Controls\n- Developing comprehensive AML programs\n- Creating monitoring systems\n- Implementing risk management protocols\n\n7. Penalties for Non-Compliance\n- Potential significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal prosecution\n- Possible loss of banking license\n\nThese obligations vary somewhat by jurisdiction but generally aim to prevent financial crimes and protect the global financial system.",
